content:
Lately I&rsquo;ve been using Browserflow to create spaced repetition flashcards quickly while browsing the internet.
To create a card, I highlight a bit of text and press &ldquo;c&rdquo;. This copies the sentence containing the highlight into the card, with the part I highlighted masked out. It&rsquo;s a cloze task, as in a masked language model. If instead I push &ldquo;b&rdquo;, it copies the full paragraph containing the highlight, again with the highlight masked out.
Usually this is a great way to quickly create my flashcards. However, sometimes I get sentences where the subject is unclear without context, e.g. &ldquo;this&rdquo; in &ldquo;Usually this is a great way to quickly create the flashcards.&rdquo; For these, it would be great to automatically rewrite the sentence with the subject pulled in from the surrounding context.
For example, &ldquo;Usually this is a great way to quickly create the flashcards&rdquo; could be rewritten as &ldquo;Usually using &ldquo;b&rdquo; and &ldquo;c&rdquo; with Browserflow is a great way to quickly create the flashcards.&rdquo;
As a second example, consider this HyperPhysics page on the Murchison Meteorite. Speaking about the Murchison Meteorite, the page says &ldquo;Seventy four amino acids were found in it, compared to the 20 which are characteristic of life.&rdquo; I&rsquo;d love to make a card saying &ldquo;Seventy four amino acids were found in the Murchison Meteorite, compared to the 20 which are characteristic of life.&rdquo;
However, if I highlight amino acids and press &ldquo;c&rdquo;, the generated card instead reads: &ldquo;Seventy four amino acids were found in it, compared to the 20 which are characteristic of life.&rdquo;
So, the challenge I present you with is: write a program that takes a sentence, and it&rsquo;s surrounding context, and rewrites the sentence so that it is clear even out of context.
Having played with GPT-3 and Codex recently, this seems well within the scope of large pretrained language models. I expect that with some careful prompting, a large language model could excel at this task without even any fine-tuning, just taking advantage of few shot learning. Is this the best or simplest approach? Likely it isn&rsquo;t, but it may be the approach that minimizes development time and is easiest to repurpose for other similar (or dissimilar) projects in the future.

This is an incomplete snippet. If I complete it, I&rsquo;ll add a link to the completed snippet here.
The default format for recording in virtual reality is a first-person perspective1. Often this is placed side-by-side with a third-person perspective of the person in real life2. I would like to see the same perspective of the player in VR and real life3.
Recording the same perspective of the player both in-game and in real life makes it easier to mentally translate between the real life movements of the player and their in-game effects. It also enables overlaying the two views for a smooth transition between the two domains. For example, you can split the screen in the middle of the player&rsquo;s body, showing half in the VR domain and half in the real domain.
This opens up the potential for low friction, minimal fuss streaming controls for streamers to use mid-game. It only takes one button or D-stick dedicated to controlling the camera to let a player toggle between streaming a fully VR perspective, a fully real life perspective, and something in between.
  First-person perspective in VR. &#x21a9;&#xfe0e;
