The purpose of the Kangaroo Auto-responder is to:
 Avoid people expecting a response from me when I don&rsquo;t realize they&rsquo;re expecting a response, e.g. because I&rsquo;ve forgotten about their message It should let me let my guard down a bit about feeling obligated to respond to people  What will it do?
It will automatically respond to messages that I&rsquo;ve seen but haven&rsquo;t responded to for 2+ hours with a kangaroo1.
The first time it sends someone a kangaroo, it will also explain:
&ldquo;[Kangaroo] Hello! This is an automated reply from the Kangaroo Auto-responder. You&rsquo;re getting this message because it looks like David might forget to reply to your message. If you want a response, you should contact him again. (Just saying &ldquo;ping&rdquo; is often enough!)&rdquo;
Text for the second time:
&ldquo;[Kangaroo] Me again. David might forget to reply to your message. In the future I&rsquo;ll just send you a picture of a Kangaroo to symbolize this. 🦘 If you ever get a picture of a Kangaroo from me, it just means David may have dropped the ball on your message and you should contact him again if you&rsquo;re expecting a response.&rdquo;
Subsequent kangaroos will be unaccompanied by explanations.
The details on exactly when to send kangaroos are still a work in progress. I don&rsquo;t want to overwhelm anyone with kangaroos. I&rsquo;m thinking about some rules: (1) only send kangaroos if there was a message of non-trivial length, e.g. more than 20 characters, (2) only send a kangaroo after I&rsquo;ve read the message; if I genuinely haven&rsquo;t seen the message yet, no need for a kangaroo, as the message will still appear as unread in my inbox, (3) if you send follow-up messages, that resets the timer on the 2 hours, (4) any messages you send within 5 minutes of me sending you a message are ineligible for triggering kangaroos (this way I don&rsquo;t need to get the last word), and (5) obviously, don&rsquo;t send a kangaroo for a message I&rsquo;ve already responded too.
To summarize, the rules of kangaroos are: You get a kangaroo if the most-recent message in our chat is non-trivial, read-by-me, written-by-you, not an immediate reply, and two-hours old.
Why kangaroos? They bounce 🤷‍♂️ ? This is kind of like a message bouncing&hellip;
  With a picture of a kangaroo, that is. Like this one: 🦘, or this: It will not send them an actual real-life kangaroo. &#x21a9;&#xfe0e;

